poem:
Rate your pain the physical therapist instructs and I am trying not to do what they say women do lowballing the number trying hard not to try so hard to be the good patient scattered assurances lining the aisles like dead petals and me left holding nothing but what’s been emptied out obviously I am over- thinking it when I settle on someplace in the middle six or seven times a week I walk past the street vendor on Broadway and say nothing while eyeing the same pom-topped hat the physical therapist asking me now for the name of that Chinese place where I sometimes go asking for the patient just before me a street vendor in need of a cheap massage as I lay the plain wreckage of my shoulders in the shallow hollows the street vendor’s body has left on the padded table in the center of the story I sometimes read to my girl a cap seller sleeps under a tree’s shade waking to find the monkeys in the branches above have plundered his wares he waves his hands shakes his fists until his rage makes him throw his cap to the ground and the monkeys mimic him and down float his caps his fury finally fulsome enough to restore what he’s lost you’ve got to find another way to move the physical therapist modeling for me the poses to mimic assuring her I won’t move what’s left of the heavy boxes later unpacking the last of them I learn about the woman who once lived here Charlotte who twisted the cap and shook out the pills Charlotte who swallowed and slipped into sleep in her last act of volition here in this bedroom where the westward windows go on longing for dawn and I am trying to move in a new way to pull the mess of sloughed hair from the bathtub drain to move in the space of another's suffering scrub the caked toothpaste from the sink make a home in the space where suffering may meet its end. 

